affiliation.description:
# affiliation

An organization that a [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/) has a connection to (through some [role](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/role/)).


### Definition

An organization that an [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/) has a connection to.


### Examples

A curator at the Swedish Museum of Natural History (where curator is the [role](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/role/) and the museum is the affiliaton).

### See also

[role](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/role/)
affiliation.x-summary: An organization that an agent has a connection to.

normalizedAgent.description:
# normalizedAgent

A person, named group of people or organization. Can be associated with a [user](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/user/) and one or more [agents](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/agent/).


### Definition

A person, named group of people or organization.


### See also

[agent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/agent/), [user](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/user/)
normalizedAgent.x-summary: A person, named group of people or organization.

role.description:
# role

An association of a [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/) with some organization (the [affiliaton](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/affiliaton/)).


### Definition

An association of an [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/) with an organization.


### Examples

A curator at the Swedish Museum of Natural History (where curator is the role and the museum is the [affiliaton](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/affiliaton/)).
role.x-summary: An association of an agent to an organization.

user.description:
# user

A user of the collection management system with a username and password. Can be associated with a [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/). Used for authentication and authorization.

agent.description:
# agent

Information about a person, named group of people or organization.


### Definition

Information about a person, named group of people or organization.


### Examples

A person named "J. Doe" can be recorded as a verbatim name “J. Doe”, standardized as “Doe, J.” and possibly connected to a known [normalizedAgent](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/normalizedAgent/) “Doe, Joe”.
agent.x-summary: Information about a person, named group of people or organization.

customObject.description: A model to be used until proper concept is defined

datePart.description:
# datePart

A reference to a particular day represented within a calendar system.

### Notes

The name is a bit problematic for two reasons:

* It is possible to store a full date, not just a partial date as the name implies
* It is possible to store a full timestamp (not just year, month and day)

timestamp.description: A date in standard format. TBA

interpretedTimestamp.description: A date in standard format, derived from day, month year.

datePart.x-summary: A reference to a day within a calendar system.

dateRange.description:
# dateRange

The start and end dates of a period and all the dates in between.

### Notes

A date range can be used to describe the temporal extension of an event (e.g. the exact start and end dates of a field trip) or to describe the uncertainty about the timing of an event (e.g. a collecting event that took place some time between the years 1800 and 1810).

id.description:
# id

A resource identifier that in combination with a resource [type](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/type) identify a single unique resource. Resource identifiers are used in many places throughout the system. This concept is important for the functioning of the system, but less so for understanding the data model at a higher level.

For more information, see the [JSON:API documentation](https://jsonapi.org/format/#document-resource-object-identification).

legacyData.description:
# legacyData

Custom data from a previous system that do not fit elsewhere in the data model.


### Definition

Data from a previous system which do not have a proper destination elsewhere in the data model.


### Examples

* An invalid collecting date, for example 2019-02-30.
* Mixed content that for some reason was not cleaned up prior to import into the system.


### Notes

Legacy data is treated as read-only data. It can be in any JSON format, but is normally added as an unordered list of name–value pairs.
legacyData.x-summary: Custom data that do not fit elsewhere in the data model.

lid.description:
# lid

A local identifier (Local ID) used internally by the system. This identifier should (inspite of what the name suggests) have the format of a Universally unique identifier (UUID).

notDefinedModel.description: A model to be used until proper concept is defined

polygon.description:
# polygon

A list of points enclosing a geographic area.


### Definition

A list of points where the last point is the same as the first, so that  the points encloses a geographic area.

vertices.description: Corners of the polygon in sane format

polygon.x-summary: A list of points enclosing a geographic area.

position.description:
# position

A point on the surface of the Earth.

### Definition

A point on the surface of the Earth.


### Notes

Could perhaps be renamed "point".

latitude.description: Latitude or northing. Prefixed with minus for coordinates on southern hemisphere.

longitude.description: Longitude or easting. Prefixed with minus for coordinates on western hemisphere.

position.x-summary: A point on the surface of the Earth.

readOnly.description:
# readOnly

A generic structure for storing custom data. Used in different parts of the system for keeping data that do not have a predefined destination. The data must be in JSON format.


## Short description

A generic structure for storing custom data.

translatedString.description:
# translatedString

A structure that is used in several places in the system to handle text in different languages.

type.description:
# type

Type is used to describe resource objects that share common attributes and relationships. In combination with a resource [id](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/id) it identifies a single unique resource. This concept is important for the functioning of the system, but less so for understanding the data model at a higher level.

For more information, see the [JSON:API documentation](https://jsonapi.org/format/#document-resource-object-identification).

verticalPosition.description:

The height of a point relative to some reference surface, such as mean sea level, a geoid, or an ellipsoid.

verticalPosition.x-summary: The height of a point relative to some reference surface.

identifierType.description:
# identifierType

The kind of [identifier](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/identifier/), for example "catalog number".


### Definition

The kind of identifier.


### Examples

* "catalog number"
* "old skeleton number"


### Notes

Some kinds of identifiers, like "catalog number", are predefined for the whole system whereas other are custom types defined for the collection (e.g. "old skeleton number").


### See also

[identifier](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/identifier/)

preparationType.description:
# preparationType

The kind of [physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) or [collectionItem](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/), for example "study skin", "dried plant", or "microscope slide".


### Definition

The kind of [physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) or [collectionItem](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/).


### Examples

* Herbarium sheet (for a [physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/))
* A herbarium sheet with two [collectionItems](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/), a plant and an microscope slide attached to the sheet: preparationTypes are "microscope slide" and "dried plant"


### Notes

The preparationType is defined within the context of the collection. In future we may want to tag preparation types with different properties, so that they can be understood outside the collection.
preparationType.x-summary: The kind of physicalUnit or collectionItem.

selectableMethod.description:
# selectableMethod

A method that can be selected for a [featureType](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/featureType/) in a [featureObservation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/featureObservation/).

place.description:
# place

A defined location that has a name and is reusable, for example a country or a lake.


### Definition

A defined location with known, fixed extension in space.


### Examples

* A named location for a Malaise trap within an insect inventory project.


### Notes

Places can have relations to other places.

New name suggestion: "location" (motivation: "place" is usually understood as something less defined, or perhaps more informal).


### See also

[locationInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/locationInformation/)
place.x-summary: A defined location with known, fixed extension in space.

acquisition.description:
# acquisition

The event of acquiring some material to the organization. Material can for example be transferred by government agencies, purchased, collected in the field by staff members, or recieved as exchanges or gifts.


### Defintion

The event of acquiring some material to the organization.
acquisition.x-summary: The event of acquiring some material to the organization.

collectingInformation.description:
# collectingInformation

Information about the collecting activity, like for example the name of a collector or the collecting method.


### Definition

Information pertaining to the activity of collecting of some material.


### Examples

The collecting method (e.g., the kind of trap) used for collecting some material.


### Notes

The purpose of this term is to keep information that is specific for the collecting activity, for example collectors, collecting method, field number etc. The general description of the collecting event, like its time and location, should be recorded under [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/).


### See also

[event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/)

collectionItem.description:
# collectionItem

The smallest recognized "thing" in the collection. This is usually a physical object but could also be a part of a physical object. For example, a moss and a lichen growing on the same piece of bark may be considered as two collection items.


### Definition

The smallest recognized "thing" in the collection. This may be a physical object or part of a physical object.


### Examples

* A skin prepared from a squirrel.
* One fish in a jar with five fishes.
* All fishes in a jar with five fishes.
* A moss and a lichen attached to the same piece of bark recognized as two collection items.


### Notes

This term represents a fundamental unit in the management of the collection. The term is permissive on what to include in a collection item, just to make the model able to fit different use cases.


### See also

[physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/)
collectionItem.x-summary: The smallest recognized "thing" in the collection.

curatorialAssessment.description:
# curatorialAssessment

Assessment of an object in the collection, more specifically its condition and whether it is present at its storage location or not.


### Definition

Assessment of the physical condition of a [physical object](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) and/or whether it is present at its normal storageLocation or not.


### Examples

* 2017-01-02 Jane Doe. Not found. On loan
* 2016-10-11 John Doe. In storage. Good condition.


### See also

[physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/)
curatorialAssessment.x-summary: Assessment of an object in the collection.

A name that associated with an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) that do not qualify as a [determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/) or a formally assigned [taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/).


### Defintion

A name that associated with an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) that do not qualify as a [determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/) or a formally assigned [taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/).

### Examples

A name on a label without any associated information.

# deathInformation

Information about the death of an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/). Typical information involves the cause of death.


### Definition
Information pertaining to the death circumstances of an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/).


### Notes

The purpose of this term is to keep information that has to do with the death of one or more organisms, for example a cause of the death. The general description of the death event, like its time and location, should be recorded under [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/).


### See also

[event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/)

determination.description:
# determination

A determination is a statement about an [individual's](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) taxon and/or type status, made by a person at a certain date. The outcome of a determination is usually a taxon name.


### Definition

The act of making a statement about an [individual's](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) taxon and/or type status, which is not itself a type status designation.


### Examples

"Phoca hispida, det. by NN, 1957"


### Notes

A *type status designation* is understood here as an explicit or implicit designation of a new type status for a specimen with respect to a taxon name. A type status designation is a nomenclatural act made through a publication and strictly regulated by a nomenclatural code. The type status designation is the primary source of a specimen's type status and should not be recorded as a determination. This is sometimes called "verified type status".

A *type status identification* on the other hand is a secondary source for the type status, and is typically written on a label that is attached to a specimen. For a type status identification (as opposed to type status designation) it is fine to record any type status, even ones that are not sanctioned by the nomenclatural codes (e.g. "topotype" or "allotype"). Because of the similarities between type status identifications and taxonomic identifications, both are here treated as determinations. In fact, if a taxon name is included in the type status identification, it may also be considered as an implicit taxonomic identification.

The outcome of the determination is in most cases a *taxon name* (that may be either scientific or vernacular). What *taxon* (i.e. taxon concept) the person intended with the determination is often difficult or even impossible to know, and has little relevance for collection management. It is usually sufficient to match the taxon name from the latest determination to the taxon concepts in the local classification currently used for the collection.


### See also

[taxonInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxonInformation/), [individual.typeStatus](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/typeStatus)
determination.x-summary: A statement about an individual's taxon and/or type status.

event.description:
# Event

An activity or occurrence at a time and location, for example the collecting of some material.


### Definition

An activity or occurrence at a particular time and location.


### Examples

An event involving the collecting of some material.


### Notes

If it is uncertain whether two specimens were collected at the same event (e.g., if they have different information sources), the information should be recorded as two separate events.

An event may have collecting- and death information.

The DINA Collections user interface may constrain the number of events associated with an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/).


### See also

[collectingInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectingInformation/), [deathInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/deathInformation/), [originInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/originInformation/)
event.x-summary: An activity or occurrence at a time and location.

featureObservation.description:
# featureObservation

An observation of some property, for example a measurement by a person or a machine at a particular time.


### Definition

The data measured, collected, perceived or noticed for some property by an agent (e.g. a person or a machine).


### Examples

* When a curator measures the wingspan and the weight of a bird, this counts as two separate observations.
* A curator observes the color of a specimen.


### Notes

This term is currently used for features for an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/). [Taxonomic determinations](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/) is currently not included, although it might be in the future. [CuratorialAssessments](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/curatorialAssessment/) apply to [collectionItems](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/) and are consequently treated as a separate concept.


### See also

[featureType](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/featureType/), [curatorialAssessment](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/curatorialAssessment/), [determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/)
featureObservation.x-summary: The data measured or noticed for some property by an agent.

identifier.description:
# identifier

A string or number that identifies something, for example a [physical object](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/), an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) or an [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/). The catalog number is an example of an identifier for a specimen.


### Definition

A name that identifies (that is, labels the identity of) something.


### Examples

* The catalog number "12345"
* The external taxon name id "9488-1" (http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idPlantNameSearch.do?id=9488-1)
* Part of a [physicaObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) (i.e. a [collectionItem](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/)) labeled "a"


### Notes

Identifiers are used for different purposes, for example for connecting information with an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) or for identifying a specimen. This term is used both for keeping record of official identifiers (like catalog numbers) and unofficial ones (like those for example found on handwritten labels attached to a specimen, or sometimes even written directly on the object).


### See also

[identifierType](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/identifierType/)
identifier.x-summary: A string or number that identifies something.

individual.description:
# individual

One or more specimens sharing a common history and individual characteristics, for example an organism, a group of organisms or a piece of mineral.


## Definition

One or more individuals with a single set of individual characteristics.


### Examples

* A specific squirrel represented by both a skin and a tissue sample in a collection.
* Three fishes in a jar of alcohol, coming from the same collecting event and representing the same taxon. The group of fishes may be treated as the individual.
* A cluster of ammonite fossils in the same piece of rock.
* A piece of mineral.


### Notes

Individual is understood in a broad sense and should be applied within its context. Thus, it should be possible to talk about individuals in for example a mineralogical collection.

This term has two purposes:

1. To keep information about the coherent unit that has a life history (or similar depending on the context) even when the unit is separated into smaller parts (as in the case where one preparation is stored separately from another).
2. To allow individual traits (color, taxon, age, sex, etc.) to be applied to a group of specimens that are treated as one unit.

You should recognize new individuals when you need to capture differences. A mix of females and males can be treated as a single individual as long as you don't need to distinguish the two sexes. When you need to distinguish the sexes, you should recognize two individuals, one for each sex. If you need to describe additional differences (e.g. color, size etc.), you may have to recognize even more individuals.

New name suggestion: “operationalIndividual” (motivation: "individual" leads one to believe that it is a single organism, which it may not be).


### Relation to other standards

* DarwinCore: [Organism](http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/Organism)

locationInformation.description:
# locationInformation

Information about the place of an event.


### Definition

Information pertaining to a specific location.


### Examples

Information about the collecting locality for a specimen, for example a transcribed text like "Frescati, Stockholm, Uppland, Sweden".


### Notes

This term is for keeping general information about a location, for example geographic coordinates or verbatim information about the location.

More specifically, the purpose of the term is:

1. to keep information about a location that is specific for an event (e.g., transcribed information about the location),
2. to keep information regarding the uncertainty about a location,
3. to describe how a location relates to some other place ("3 km NW of"), and
4. to document the source for some information (so that interpretations can be traced).
locationInformation.x-summary: Information about the place of an event.

originInformation.description:
# originInformation

Information about the physical or genetic origin of an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/). This could for example be information on where an individual previously lived. The information may be associated with an [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/).


### Defintion
Information pertaining to the origin of an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/).


### Example

An [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) may have more than one [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/) connected with origin information. For example: a lion first lived in Africa (origin event 1), then was placed in a Zoo in Europe (origin event 2), and finally escaped into the wild (origin event 3) where it was later killed and collected (death and collecting event).


### Notes

The purpose of this term is to keep information that has to do with the origin of [individuals](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/). This could involve both the genetic and the physical origin. This term concerns the origin of individuals, not the provenance of specimens. The general description of the origin event, like its time and location, should be recorded under [event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/).


### See also

[event](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/event/)
originInformation.x-summary: Information about the origin of an individual.

specimen.description:
# specimen

The "things" registered under the same catalog number.


### Defintion

The "things" registered under the same catalog number.


### Notes

This is a flexible concept that can be used differently depending on the collection type or the collection's cataloging practices. The purpose is to support different kinds of collections that would otherwise be difficult to fit within the same system. For example, a specimen may in some collections correspond to a single physical object, whereas other collections may treat multiple physical objects from the same gathering event or the same individual as one specimen.


### Examples

* A skin and a skeleton from the same squirrel recognized as one specimen. Hence, the specimen corresponds to an individual.
* A skin and a skeleton from the same squirrel recognized as two separate specimens. Hence, specimen corresponds to a physical object.

taxonInformation.description:
# taxonInformation

Information about an [individual's](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) taxon, for example its accepted name according to the local classification. This term can also hold other taxon names which are not part of a [determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/). For the moment is type information also included here.


### Definition

Information about the taxon to which an [individual](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/individual/) is currently assigned according to the local classification, or other names that has been associated with the individual that do not qualify as [determinations](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/).


### Examples

"Pusa hispida" is the accepted name for a taxon in the local classification, and "Phoca hispida" one of its synonyms. Consequently, "Pusa hispida" should be the locally accepted name (curatorial name) for a specimen that has been determined as "Phoca hispida".


### Notes

The purpose of this concept is:

* To keep information of the currently accepted name for an individual
* To keep information that is specific to type specimens (e.g. type status, typified name)
* To accommodate taxon-related legacy data that do not fit into taxon in the taxonomyService or into determination

The data model is flexible, and it is possible to treat a locally accepted name for a specimen as a determination. One might then ask if there are cases when this should not be done? In principle, you should not use determination *if you cannot assume that the taxon name properly represents an original determination, and if it is impossible to assess whether that is the case*.

Imagine for example that the text on a determination label reads "not taxon x", while the name "taxon x" has been recorded as the name for the specimen in an old system (this can happen in collections where taxonomy is tightly connected to storage, and it is important to just record some name). Without other information, it would be impossible to know that "taxon x" was derived from the text "not taxon x". Since you cannot be sure of where the information comes from, there would be no way to correct the erroneous determination record.

Another case is when a name at a different rank, let say a family, has been recorded from a determination to a subfamily written on a label, without saying anything about how the transformation was done. There can also be undocumented taxonomic interpretations at the same level, like when an original determination to "Phoca hispida" is recorded as just "Pusa hispida".

For the moment is type information included as part of this model. In future, one may want to recognize this as a separate concept.


### See also

[determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/), [taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/)
taxonInformation.x-summary: Information about the taxon to which an individual is assigned.

physicalObject.description:
# physicalObject

The smallest recognized physical "thing" in the collection. Typical examples are a skin preparation and a herbarium sheet. A physical object represents one or more [collectionItems](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/).


### Definition

The smallest recognized physical "thing" in the collection.


### Examples

* A herbarium sheet with three plants mounted on it (possibly three collection items)
* A mounted skin of a squirrel (one [collectionItem](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/))
* A jar with two fishes (possibly two [collectionItems](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/))
* A tree branch with two birds mounted on it (possibly two [collectionItems](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/))


### Notes

The physical object is the physical thing that you do something with when you manage your collection. This could for example be the thing stored on the shelf, sent on loan or received from a donator. Physical objects change over time. Imagine for example a jar of 5 fishes first treated as one physical object "A". In response to a loan request, a new physical object "B" is created with one of the fishes and sent to the borrower. When the loan is returned, the fish is put back into the original container ("A"), thereby ending the existence of object "B".


### See also

[collectionItem](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/collectionItem/)
physicalObject.x-summary: The smallest recognized physical "thing" in the collection.

storageLocation.description:
# storageLocation

A space for storing [physicalObjects](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) in a collection.


### Definition

A dedicated space, at any level in a hierarchy, for storing one or more [physicalObjects](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/) in a collection.


### Examples

* "room 123"
* "Swedish Coleoptera"
* "the bone room"


### Notes

A storage location is usually a fixed space (like a room, shelf or cabinet) but could also be a "floating location". This latter kind is especially common when objects are sorted by taxonomy. Instead of having a fixed physical position are floating storage locations placed in relation to other storage locations nearby. For example, the objects representing the genus *Phoca* may be placed after those of *Pagophilus*, but before those of *Pusa*. Storage locations may be arranged in a hierarchy, irrespective of whether they have fixed positions or not.


### See also

[physicalObject](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/physicalObject/)
storageLocation.x-summary: A dedicated space for storing physical objects.

taxon.description:
# taxon

A taxonomic group of any rank, such as a species or family, or class used to keep information about a locally used taxon concept.


### Definition

A taxonomic group of any rank, such as a species, family, or class.


### Examples

The species that includes the type specimen for the name "Pusa hispida", which may also be referred to by the synonym "Phoca hispida".


### Notes

The purpose of this term is to keep information about locally used taxon concepts. These concepts do not have to be used elsewhere. The local classification is the combination of all the names and their relations. In the local classification, each taxon has an accepted taxon name at same rank as the taxon (more precisely, the taxon gets its rank from the accepted name). The accepted name may have synonyms at any rank.


### See also

[determination](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/determination/), [taxonInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxonInformation/)
taxon.x-summary: A taxonomic group of any rank, such as a species or family.

taxonName.description:
# taxonName

A name of a taxon (at any rank) that may be either a scientific name or a vernacular name.


### Definition

A scientific or vernacular name of a [taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/) at any rank.


### Examples

* "Phoca hispida" (species)
* "Phocidae" (family)


### Notes

Scientific names do not have to be validly published according to a nomenclatural code. It is for example often desirable to use informal names for managing taxonomic groups that are poorly known. For the purpose of collection management, one often want to be pragmatic regarding the use of taxon names.

A taxon name may or may not be associated with a [taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/).


### See also

[taxon](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxon/), [taxonInformation](/dataModelDocs/0.4.2-0.3.7/models/taxonInformation/)
taxonName.x-summary: A scientific or vernacular name of a taxon.
